TY  - JOUR
AU  - Diermeier, Daniel
AU  - Vlaicu, Razvan
T1  - Executive Control and Legislative Success
PY  - 2011
Y1  - 2011/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdq030
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 78
IS  - 3
SP  - 846
EP  - 871
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The higher legislative success of parliamentary governments relative to presidential governments has been used to argue that legislative success is driven by parliamentary governments' superior agenda power or their control of legislative majorities. We show that this approach is at odds with some of the empirical regularities across and within political systems. We then propose a legislative bargaining model to elucidate this puzzle. In the model, the policies of a confidence-dependent parliamentary government enjoy more predictable support from governing coalition members because their short-term policy goals are less important than the government's survival. Coalition support is stronger when the government has more agenda power and is weaker with a larger ruling coalition. We explore the empirical implications of these findings and their consequences for the comparative study of legislative institutions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdq030
ER  - 



